 stressed the putative cultural differences distinguishing “savage” societies from their “civilized” counterparts. This incisive book also shows that Burke’s argument had lasting implications, as his development of these two justifications for empire prefigured later intellectual defenses of British imperialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aImperialismy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  a18th century british empire.  a18th century imperialism.  abritish colonialism.  abritish history.  abritish political thought.  aburkes defense of empire.  acivilized societies.  acultural differences.  acultural similarities.  afounding father of conservatism.  afrench revolution.  alogic of empire.  amodern conservatism.  aorientalism.  aornamentalism.  aothering.  apolitical philosophy.  apolitics and government of great britain.  asavage societies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052028782240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096286640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962866423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520962866/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY